'''Family Fairness''' was a program run by the [[Immigration and Naturalization Services]] in the United States from October 21, 1987 to November 29, 1990, under the presidencies of [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[George H.W. Bush]] and under INS commissioners [[Alan C. Nelson]] and [[Gene McNary]].<ref name=aic>{{cite web|url = https://www.americanimmigrationcouncil.org/research/reagan-bush-family-fairness-chronological-history|title = Reagan-Bush Family Fairness: A Chronological History|date = December 9, 2014|accessdate = February 5, 2017|publisher = American Immigration Council}}</ref><ref name=huffpo>{{cite web|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/marshall-fitz/the-bush-family-fairness-_b_6319760.html|title = The Bush Family Fairness Plan Is the True Precursor to the Presidentâ€™s Executive Actions on Immigration|last = Fitz|first = Marshall|date = December 15, 2014|publisher = ''[[Huffington Post]]''}}</ref><ref name=thehill>{{cite web|url = http://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/foreign-policy/219463-when-reagan-and-ghw-bush-took-bold-executive-action-on|title = When Reagan and GHW Bush took bold executive action on immigration|last = Noferi|first = Mark|date = October 2, 2014|accessdate = February 5, 2016|publisher = ''[[The Hill]]''}}</ref> The program was created through executive action, in order to meet the problem of "split-eligibility" families created by the [[Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986]], pending legislation that would address the issue.<ref name=aic/> The [[Immigration Act of 1990]] replaced it with a legislatively sanctioned Family Unity Program, that continues to be in force today.<ref name=aic/>

